:: StoryTitle
The Good Engine

:: StoryData
{
  "ifid": "DDBE9A6A-18D5-457B-AD07-CD3E6DD74731",
  "format": "SugarCube",
  "format-version": "2.37.3",
  "start": "FlightPrep"
}

:: StoryInit
/* SCENARIO TITLE:      The Good Engine
   AUDIENCE:            General Aviation Pilots (multi-engine)
   TONE:                Professional
   PRIMARY TOPIC:       The single-engine arrival: destination selection, energy
                        and configuration discipline, and the commit gate, in an
                        airplane whose OEI go-around is marginal to imaginary.
   SECONDARY TOPIC:     Drift-down planning over ridges, declaring for priority,
                        passenger pressure against diverting.
   AIRCRAFT/EQUIPMENT:  1966 Piper PA-30 Twin Comanche B, N8331Y. Lycoming
                        IO-320-B1A, 160 hp per side, non-turbo. Full-feathering
                        Hartzell props, no unfeathering accumulators. Panel
                        placarded in MPH. Vmc 90 MPH (78 kt). Vyse 105 MPH
                        (91 kt). SE service ceiling at today's weight about
                        6,600 density altitude. Gross 3,600 lb, today 3,250 lb.
   SETTING:             KLEX (Lexington KY) to KLWB (Greenbrier Valley WV),
                        about 200 nm. Friday, October 16, mid-afternoon. Story
                        opens over southern West Virginia, LEFT engine already
                        secured and feathered, 15 minutes after shutdown.
   WEATHER:             Broken deck bases about 5,500 MSL with ragged holes,
                        tops about 7,000 with taller swells, patchy ridgetop
                        obscuration east, haze in the valleys, light wind aloft,
                        valley surface winds nearly calm.
   ADM THEMES:          Destination selection OEI, commit-gate discipline,
                        declaring for priority, energy management, restart
                        temptation, passenger pressure, conflicting weather.
   HAZARDOUS ATTITUDES: Macho (press to destination, refuse priority),
                        invulnerability (restart as insurance), impulsivity
                        (panic go-around), resignation (hold and burn altitude).
   PROTAGONIST:         Curt Weaver, 41, commercial ASEL/AMEL, 850 hrs TT,
                        180 multi, co-owner of the airplane.
   PASSENGER:           Dev Malhotra, 38, brother-in-law. Non-pilot.
   TOTAL ENDINGS:       13 (1 full success, 3 qualified success,
                        2 qualified-with-scare, 2 friction/social cost,
                        2 delay/diversion, 2 aircraft damage (gear-up,
                        overrun), 1 fatal, reachable only through a chain
                        of the worst available choices)
   MIN DECISION DEPTH:  4 story decisions on every path (audit enforces)
   TIMED DECISIONS:     No
   ESTIMATED DURATION:  20-30 minutes
   VERSION:             1.0    LAST REVIEWED: July 2026    REVIEWER: (pending)
   DESIGN NOTE:         The engine failure is over before the story starts. The
                        drill here is the arrival: where the good engine takes
                        you, and whether you ever need the go-around you do not
                        have. Airports, runways, elevations, and frequencies are
                        real and verified. Weather is fictional but coherent.
*/
<<set $readWeather to false>>
<<set $readAircraft to false>>
<<set $readChart to false>>
<<set $readFields to false>>
<<set $pathArray to []>>
<<set $badchoices to 0>>
<<set $declared to "none">>
<<set $dest to "">>
<<set $held to false>>
<<set $routing to "">>
<<set $popup to false>>
<<set $restartTried to false>>
<<set $shopCalled to false>>
<<set $gateBriefed to false>>
<<set $gearDown to false>>
<<set $config to "">>
<<set $altNow to 7500>>
<<set $swingBack to false>>
<<set $bkwTouch to "">>
<<set $atisPulled to false>>
<<set $groundPlan to "">>

