:: End_LWB_VmcRoll [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: eleven seconds"])>>
Full throttle. Nose up. Left bank, away from the runway, the go-around flown the way a thousand two-engine go-arounds trained your hands to fly it.

The right engine delivers everything it has, and all of it is yaw. The nose swings left into the dead engine, the bank you commanded helps it, and the airspeed, which was 96, becomes 91, then 88<<if $config is "late">> as the gear you rushed out on short final drags at full extension<</if>>. The rudder reaches its stop. At three hundred feet above the Greenbrier Valley the left wing stops flying, and the roll that follows is smooth, unhurried, and past vertical in under two seconds.

The Twin Comanche strikes the pasture short of the airport fence eleven seconds after the words "go around." There is no fire. The ELT does its work, and the county equipment that nobody asked to stand by arrives in six minutes, which on this evening is five and a half minutes more than the difference would have needed.

The NTSB writes it up in the spare language reserved for the most documented accident sequence in twin-engine aviation: loss of directional control following an attempted single-engine go-around, bank toward the inoperative engine, airspeed below Vmc. The report does not mention the tee time, the rental car, or how reasonable every mile of the afternoon felt from inside it.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>An airplane that had flown fifty stable miles on one engine was destroyed in eleven seconds, not by the failure, but by the arrival. A go-around was attempted below four hundred feet with full power on the right engine, a pitch-up, and a bank into the dead engine. Airspeed fell through Vmc, directional control was lost, and no altitude existed in which to recover. This is the Vmc roll, and at pattern altitude it is unsurvivable nearly every time it occurs.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>No single decision did this. Four did, in a row, each one narrowing what the next could fix. First, canceling advisories fifty miles out: the tower sequenced a Skyhawk into your final because you had made yourself ordinary, so the go-around instruction got issued at all. <<if $restartTried>>Second, the airstart: reopening a closed case against the physical evidence, which spent five hundred feet and, more expensively, your composure.<</if>> <<if $config is "late">>Then the clean-to-the-bottom energy plan, which meant the final approach was a rush of configuration instead of a stabilized procedure, and left the airplane dirty, slow, and mid-transition at the worst moment.<</if>> Then the absence of any briefed commit gate, so "go around" arrived with no pre-decided answer standing in its way. And last, the reflex itself: the two-engine go-around, flown by hands that were never given a different plan to hold. The instruction from the tower was legal to refuse. "Unable" was one word away, and the survivable compliance, wings level, clean first, straight ahead, was also sitting there. Impulsivity took the controls because nothing had been briefed to stop it.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Three defenses existed, any one of which ends this story on a ramp. Declare, and the runway is sterile. Brief the gate, and below four hundred feet "go around" is answered with "unable, landing." And if a go-around must happen anyway, the only version this airplane sells is wings level at blue line, cleaned up, straight ahead, never a bank toward the feathered side. Vmc is not a certification abstraction. It is 90 miles per hour, painted red, eighteen inches from where your eyes were pointed.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The good engine took this airplane exactly as far as the planning deserved. It did not have to end at the scene of the folk saying. It never does.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
