:: End_BKW_Saved [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: Beckley, then the hour east"])>>
The shuttle driver has opinions about the interstate and shares all of them. By 5:30 you have a rental, by 5:45 Merle has heard the whole story twice ("you did the flying part fine, now don't touch it"), and Gwen has already reached the Beckley shop by some partner telepathy of her own. The airplane will get its cowl opened Monday by people with a parts account.

The drive east is an hour of gold light on ridgelines. Dev calls his golf buddies from the passenger seat and tells the story with hand gestures you can hear. Dinner in Lewisburg happens. The 8:40 tee time happens. On fourteen, Dev three-putts and announces that his playing partner landed on one engine yesterday, so nobody gets to complain about anything.

Sunday evening, driving home, you pass the Beckley exit and both of you look right, toward the hilltop, without saying anything.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>You took the nearest suitable runway, managed a high-density-altitude arrival on one engine, and landed with nothing bent and nothing owed. <<if $bkwTouch is "firm">>The picture-fixing power reduction on final bought a sink rate you then had to buy back, and the arrival was firm because of it.<<else>>You flew the indicated numbers and let the scenery hurry, which is precisely the discipline thin air demands.<</if>> The weekend lost an evening hour and kept everything else.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Beckley's case at your first decision was proximity, and proximity is a powerful, legitimate argument with one engine running. Its price tag was elevation: a field a half-mile up, where your single-engine climb budget was thinnest. You paid the price knowingly and it held. <<if $routing is "spiral">>The overhead spiral kept the runway in glide range the whole descent, the most conservative geometry available, bought at the cost of a few extra minutes aloft.<<elseif $routing is "low">>The straight-in you flew was the conveyor-belt arrival this airplane wanted, though the low hallway that got you there put a thousand-foot ceiling on your options for six long miles.<<else>>The planned, flat straight-in was the conveyor-belt arrival this airplane wanted: no base turn, no bank, no surprises.<</if>> <<if $declared is "emergency">>Declaring rolled one county truck and cost one word. It was standing at midfield being unnecessary, which is the correct place for it.<<elseif $declared is "advisory">>Your plain statement to approach kept the record honest without claiming priority. Workable, and one word short of the full service.<<else>>Canceling radar services nine minutes early saved you nothing and spent your only high cover. Had the good engine faltered in the descent, the first anyone would have heard of it was an ELT.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Closest field is a fine answer when the field is suitable, and suitability at altitude means doing density-altitude arithmetic before final, not during the flare. The card's numbers, indicated airspeed flown faithfully, protect against the eye's sea-level calibration. Fifteen minutes of stable, trimmed OEI cruise is cheap. A rushed descent to a thin-air runway is where that cheapness gets spent.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Fly the needle in thin air. The scenery is lying to you at exactly the moment you most want to believe it.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readChart to false>><<set $readFields to false>><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $dest to "">><<set $held to false>><<set $routing to "">><<set $popup to false>><<set $restartTried to false>><<set $shopCalled to false>><<set $gateBriefed to false>><<set $gearDown to false>><<set $config to "">><<set $altNow to 7500>><<set $swingBack to false>><<set $bkwTouch to "">><<set $atisPulled to false>><<set $groundPlan to "">><</link>>
</div>
