:: End_BKW_Slow [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: overnight in Beckley on purpose"])>>
The hotel by the interstate has a room, a diner attached, and a parking lot view of the hill you just landed on. You do the calls slowly over coffee: Merle first ("smart, staying put, you'd be amazed how many guys wreck a car the same night they save an airplane"), then Gwen, then the logbook entry, written in a hand that gets steadier with each line.

Dev misses the Friday steak dinner his buddies drove in for, and takes it like a champ, which is to say he mentions it only twice. At dawn you drive the hour east through fog pooled in the hollows, and Dev makes the 8:40 tee time with twenty minutes and one gas-station biscuit to spare. He plays the front nine like a man who slept badly and the back nine like a man glad to be anywhere.

The airplane waits on the Beckley ramp, tied down, cowl streaks going chalky, patient as furniture.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>You landed at the nearest suitable field and then made an unfashionable call: you stopped moving. The adrenaline bill from an engine failure and a single-engine arrival got paid in a Beckley hotel instead of on a dusk mountain highway. It cost your brother-in-law a steak dinner and cost you nothing that shows on any inspection.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Post-event fatigue is the least-briefed threat in an emergency, because it arrives after the emergency is officially over. The pilot who feathers an engine, flies a thin-air approach, and shuts down clean is spent in ways that do not show up until a curve does. Recognizing that, out loud, with a disappointed passenger in earshot, is the same discipline as the feather drill: identify, verify, secure. <<if $bkwTouch is "firm">>The one wobble in the flying was chasing the sea-level picture with power on final, which traded airspeed discipline for a sink rate and a firm arrival.<<else>>The flying itself held the card's numbers all the way down, thin-air picture and all.<</if>> <<if $declared is "emergency">>In the air you took the full service, one word, one county truck, zero regrets.<<elseif $declared is "advisory">>On the radio you told the truth and claimed nothing, a serviceable middle road.<<else>>On the radio you went dark nine minutes early, which cost nothing today and is the kind of habit that costs everything eventually.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>IMSAFE applies after the airplane is tied down, too. Fatigue and stress are two of its six letters, and both were maxed. The trade you made, a dinner for a rested driver on mountain roads, is the same trade you made at altitude, a weekend's convenience for margin. Consistency between the cockpit version of you and the parking-lot version is the actual skill.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The emergency is not over when the props stop. It is over when the adrenaline is, and that runs on its own clock.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
