:: End_BKW_LongStop [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: long touchdown, hot brakes"])>>
You put it on the pavement mains-first, twenty-eight hundred feet in, and go to work. Brakes in firm, steady squeezes, nose held straight, the far fence growing at a rate you will remember longer than you would like. The Twin Comanche stops with about eight hundred feet of asphalt left, brakes ticking and stinking, tires flat-spotted just enough to make Merle sigh next week.

You sit at the turnoff for a moment before taxiing. Dev looks at the remaining runway, then back down the long stretch behind, doing his own version of the math.

<div class="pax-quote">"So that white fence back there," he says. "Was that ever, like, a participant in this?"</div>

"It was interested," you say, and taxi in. The evening survives: rental car, the drive east, a late dinner, the tee time. But you eat that night with the far fence still in your peripheral vision, and when Dev tells the story to his buddies he calls it "the water-ski landing," and you let him, because it costs less than explaining that the extra ten miles an hour was a gift you gave yourself.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>Ten miles an hour of "insurance" speed became a half-mile of float in thin air, and the landing that followed consumed nearly all of a 6,750-foot runway. You accepted the long touchdown, braked with discipline, and stopped with hundreds, not thousands, of feet in reserve. No damage beyond tire wear and brake heat. No margin left, either.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The extra speed was the invulnerability attitude speaking fluent aerodynamics: it sounded like conservatism and behaved like risk. On one engine, airspeed above the card's number is not stored climb, it is stored float, payable at the far end where the fence lives. Density altitude then compounded it: at thirty-eight hundred feet, the same indicated speed carries more true speed and more energy into the flare. Once floating, your best remaining choice was exactly the one you made: put it down and use every foot deliberately, rather than gamble on a go-around the performance card had already priced at approximately nothing.<<if $gateBriefed>> Note that the gate you briefed protected the approach but said nothing about touchdown energy. A complete brief has both: a commit altitude and a speed at the fence.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>OEI approach speed discipline is the whole ballgame in a light twin: Vyse to short final, the card's fence speed over the fence, no gratuities. If a landing is going long, the decision point is at the gate, high, where a reject still exists as a maneuver, not in ground effect where physics has repossessed it. You flew the recovery well. The lesson lives one decision earlier.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Extra airspeed on one engine is not insurance. It is a loan, and the far fence is the collection agent.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readChart to false>><<set $readFields to false>><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $dest to "">><<set $held to false>><<set $routing to "">><<set $popup to false>><<set $restartTried to false>><<set $shopCalled to false>><<set $gateBriefed to false>><<set $gearDown to false>><<set $config to "">><<set $altNow to 7500>><<set $swingBack to false>><<set $bkwTouch to "">><<set $atisPulled to false>><<set $groundPlan to "">><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_BKW_Scrape [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: the go-around that barely was"])>>
Throttle to the stop. Flaps up in stages. Gear handle up, and the transit takes its seven seconds while the airplane decides what it thinks of all this. What it thinks is: not much. The nose comes up and the climb does not come with it. You accelerate in ground effect the length of the remaining runway, cross the far fence at fifty feet with the stall horn tasting the air, and the ground beyond keeps sinking away toward a creek hollow, which is the only reason the picture works at all.

One fifty a minute. Maybe. The trees on the far rise slide beneath at a distance you will not repeat out loud. It takes four miles to claw back to pattern altitude, one wide flat left turn at a bank angle you meter like medicine, and the second approach is a different religion: 105 to the fence, not a mile an hour more. The landing is almost sarcastic in its normalcy.

On the ramp, neither of you speaks for a moment. Dev finally exhales. "Okay. The boring one. Do the boring one every time."

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>A float born of extra approach speed ended in a low-altitude single-engine go-around, the exact maneuver the performance card prices at roughly zero feet per minute once the gear and flaps join in. It succeeded by a margin measured in treetops: light weight, falling terrain past the fence, a straight-ahead climbout with no bank, and luck arranged in your favor. The second approach, flown at card speeds, was uneventful.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Two errors stacked. The first was carrying ten extra miles an hour down final as "insurance," which converted directly into float. The second was rejecting from inside ground effect, where a single-engine go-around in a PA-30 at thirty-eight hundred density altitude is a test flight, not a procedure. The honest options at that point were a long, disciplined touchdown or the one you chose, and only one of them keeps the outcome in your hands. Impulsivity supplied the vote: the float felt wrong, so full power felt like taking charge.<<if $gateBriefed>> The gate you briefed on the way down was honored right up until it mattered most. A commit gate that dissolves in the flare was a hope, not a gate.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Below the gate, in this airplane, on one engine, the landing is the answer even when it is a long one: 6,750 feet forgives a half-mile float. The go-around decision belongs at altitude, where the card says the maneuver still exists. And the prevention is upstream of all of it: fly Vyse, cross the fence at the card's speed, and the float never gets born.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>You briefed that there is no go-around below the gate. The airplane meant it even if you didn't.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readChart to false>><<set $readFields to false>><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $dest to "">><<set $held to false>><<set $routing to "">><<set $popup to false>><<set $restartTried to false>><<set $shopCalled to false>><<set $gateBriefed to false>><<set $gearDown to false>><<set $config to "">><<set $altNow to 7500>><<set $swingBack to false>><<set $bkwTouch to "">><<set $atisPulled to false>><<set $groundPlan to "">><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_BKW_Overrun [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: off the end at Beckley"])>>
You push it on. The mains touch at 110 with three thousand feet already spent, the nosewheel slams down a heartbeat later, and you stand on the brakes hard enough to feel the anti-nothing this 1966 airplane was built with: tires howl, the airplane squirms, rubber gives up its grip in stuttering chirps. The numbers do not work and you watch them not work, all the way to the end, where the Twin Comanche leaves the pavement at fifteen knots, rumbles through the mowed overrun, and stops when the nose gear finds soft earth and folds with a sound like a dropped toolbox.

The props were stopped or nearly so. The belly is whole. You and Dev climb out into grass to the sound of the county truck starting its roll somewhere behind the FBO, invited or not.

Dev looks back at the runway, all sixty-seven hundred and fifty feet of it, lying there used up. "We had all of that," he says, not unkindly. "And we used all of that."

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>Extra approach speed floated the airplane a half-mile down a 6,750-foot runway, and instead of accepting the float's verdict with a disciplined long landing or rejecting at altitude where a reject still existed, you forced the airplane onto the pavement hot and trusted the brakes to fix it. They could not. The airplane went off the end at low speed, folded its nose gear in the overrun, and turned an inconvenience into an incident: an NTSB 830 conversation, an insurance claim, and a Twin Comanche on jacks until spring.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Three decisions in a row leaned the same direction. Ten extra miles an hour for "insurance." A float accepted without a plan. Then force applied as a substitute for the plan: nosewheel down, brakes to the floor, the macho attitude's signature move of ending the situation by insisting. Energy does not respond to insistence. The genuinely bitter note is that the long landing was sitting right there: touch at twenty-eight hundred feet with card speeds and the rollout works, barely but honestly.<<if $declared is "none">> And having gone quietly off everyone's radar earlier, you got to explain from a field phone what nobody was standing by to see.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Landing distance problems are solved at the fence, with speed, or not at all. The stabilized-approach habit exists precisely for this: on speed at the gate or the approach ends there, at altitude, as a decision instead of an event. Once floating in ground effect on one engine, the remaining skill is acceptance: put it down straight, brake to the physics, and let the runway be as long as it is.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The runway was never too short. The airplane was too fast, and it was too fast because you asked it to be.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readChart to false>><<set $readFields to false>><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $dest to "">><<set $held to false>><<set $routing to "">><<set $popup to false>><<set $restartTried to false>><<set $shopCalled to false>><<set $gateBriefed to false>><<set $gearDown to false>><<set $config to "">><<set $altNow to 7500>><<set $swingBack to false>><<set $bkwTouch to "">><<set $atisPulled to false>><<set $groundPlan to "">><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_CRW_GearUp [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: gear-up on runway 23"])>>
You keep the bank in and run the flow from memory, in the turn, on one engine, eyes jumping between the airspeed, the runway, and the hillside. Props forward. Flaps first notch. The base turn tightens. Tower says something about a wind check. Final assembles itself at the last moment, high and then suddenly not, and the round-out feels strange, quiet, floaty, and the part of your brain that keeps score offers its note a half-second before the belly touches: <<if $config is "early" or $config is "briefed">>you put the wheels down once today, on the straight-in, and took them back up for the swing. They never came down again.<<else>>in ninety seconds of turning flow, the gear handle is the item that never got its turn.<</if>>

The airplane lands on its keel with a long, grinding hush, both props curling, and slides eight hundred feet along runway 23's centerline before it stops, straight, level, and eleven inches shorter than it woke up. You and Dev step out onto the wing without a scratch between you. The trucks arrive in ninety seconds either way. It is very quiet on the hilltop, except for the crash truck's light bar ticking around and around.

Dev stands on the runway looking at the propeller tips. "We're okay," he says, testing it. "We're okay."

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>An offer of a better wind became an unstabilized, low-altitude reposition flown on one engine, and the before-landing flow, already displaced once by the runway change, lost its most important item. The airplane touched down gear-up on runway 23 and slid to a stop. Two people walked away from a bent airplane that flew perfectly the entire time.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The chain is short and common. First, a late runway change accepted at eleven hundred feet, trading a briefed, stabilized final for a tight circuit in haze. Second, the decision to finish the circuit after it turned busy, when a bailout to the straight-in was still on the table and had been offered by your own instincts. The gear was not forgotten by carelessness. It was displaced by workload that was optional, purchased seconds earlier, at retail. That is impulsivity in its Sunday clothes: the offer sounded like a favor, so it was accepted like an instruction.<<if $declared is "none">> Underneath it, the same pilot who minimized the emergency on frequency accepted extra workload to fly a "normal" arrival. The airplane was never normal today. Handling it normally was the error with the paint on it.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>A tower's runway offer is a question, and "unable, we'll keep 5" is a complete answer. Eight knots of tailwind on 6,215 feet of runway was a solved problem the moment you briefed it. When a change does get accepted, the flow starts over from the top, out loud, wings level, and any approach that cannot be stabilized by short final gets abandoned early, which on one engine means it gets abandoned high. The gear-up landing itself was, mechanically, well flown. That is the epitaph of most gear-up landings.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Late runway changes are workload wearing a gift bow. On one engine, decline the gift, or pay for it with a restarted checklist and altitude you may not have.</p>
</div>
